            <div class="prose max-w-none" x-show="lang === 'en'" x-cloak>
                <h2>A Confusing Real Scenario</h2>
<p>Last Wednesday, a sigh came from a certain workstation. Li, the campaign manager, frowned at the backend data: an ad for Bluetooth earphones had a CTR of 4.2%, nearly double the industry average, but after running for 8 consecutive days, only 3 orders were generated with a CPA of $47.</p>
<p>"This creative clearly runs well, so why won't it sell?"</p>
<p>This is a common scene in overseas marketing teams. High CTR often misleads teams into thinking the creative is excellent, but little do they know, there's a conversion gap between 'runnable' and 'sellable' creatives.</p>
<h2>Problem Diagnosis: What CTR Masks</h2>
<p>During the review meeting, Li pulled complete funnel data:</p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Metric</th>
<th>Value</th>
<th>Industry Benchmark</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>CTR</td>
<td>4.2%</td>
<td>2.1%</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>CPC</td>
<td>$0.38</td>
<td>$0.52</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Add to Cart</td>
<td>1.8%</td>
<td>3.2%</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Purchase</td>
<td>0.3%</td>
<td>1.1%</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p>The problem surfaced: the creative attracted 'curiosity clicks' rather than 'purchase intent.' Users clicked in expecting something different from what they found, or the landing page failed to deliver the value promised in the ad, resulting in high clicks but low conversions.</p>
<p><strong>Core Judgment Criteria</strong>: Sellable creatives should have both excellent CTR and CVR, or at least CVR shouldn't drag down performance. A standalone high CTR is often a 'clickbait' creative, using gimmicks to attract clicks without conveying real product value.</p>
<h2>Three Actions to Determine if Creative is 'Runnable' or 'Sellable'</h2>
<h3>Action 1: Break Down Traffic Source Structure</h3>
<p>Open Meta Ads Manager and segment data by placement. Li's creative had the highest CTR on Instagram Stories (5.8%), but only 0.2% conversion rate in News Feed. This indicates the creative suited the swipe-through browsing context but failed to convince users with purchase intent.</p>
<p><strong>Operation Steps</strong>:<br />
1. Export conversion data segmented by placement<br />
2. Compare CTR and CVR correlation across different placements<br />
3. If CTR is high but CVR is extremely low at certain placements, the creative is 'runnable but not sellable'</p>
<h3>Action 2: Check Consistency Between Creative and Landing Page</h3>
<p>Li replayed the ad: the first 3 seconds showed earphones being used in a gym setting, with the headline "Exercise Without Restrictions." But the landing page hero image was a pure white background product shot. Users clicked expecting the scene experience but received a standard e-commerce detail page—expectation mismatch led to low add-to-cart rates.</p>
<p><strong>Quick Diagnostic Checklist</strong>:<br />
- Is the core value proposition promised in the ad visible above the fold?<br />
- Does the usage scenario shown in the creative align with the landing page?<br />
- Is the CTA button's guided action logically connected to the page flow?</p>
<h3>Action 3: Run AB Intent Testing on Creatives</h3>
<p>Run both the existing 'runnable' creative and a 'sellable' hypothesis creative simultaneously for 3 days, observing differences in user behavior paths. Li's team created a new creative: the first 3 seconds directly showed the product实物 and price range, clearly conveying "high cost-performance Bluetooth earphones." Test results showed:</p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Creative Type</th>
<th>CTR</th>
<th>Add to Cart</th>
<th>Purchase</th>
<th>CPA</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Scenario-based (Runnable)</td>
<td>4.2%</td>
<td>1.8%</td>
<td>0.3%</td>
<td>$47</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Value-based (Sellable)</td>
<td>2.6%</td>
<td>3.5%</td>
<td>1.2%</td>
<td>$12</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p>The value-based creative's CTR dropped by 38%, but CPA was only one-quarter of the original.</p>
<h2>Action Items: Creative Iteration Direction</h2>
<p>Based on the diagnosis, Li's team developed the following adjustment strategy:</p>
<ol>
<li><strong>Retain scenario-based creatives for prospecting</strong>: Use as low-cost traffic drivers during cold start periods</li>
<li><strong>Push value-based creatives for conversion</strong>: After accumulating users with brand awareness, use creatives with clear value propositions to capture conversions</li>
<li><strong>Optimize landing page alignment</strong>: Create dedicated landing pages for scenario-based creatives, preserving the usage scenario elements</li>
<li><strong>Build creative classification tags</strong>: Label 'prospecting' and 'conversion' creatives for easier batch management</li>
</ol>
<h2>Results and Insights</h2>
<p>In the second week after adjustment, the Bluetooth earphone ad group's CPA dropped to $14, with daily orders increasing from 0.4 to 2.1. Although high-CTR creatives were deprioritized, overall ROI improved significantly.</p>
<p><strong>Key Takeaway</strong>: When reviewing creatives, don't be fooled by single metrics. 'Runnable' creatives are responsible for spending money to generate buzz, while 'sellable' creatives are responsible for actually bringing revenue. Distinguishing between the two requires examining both traffic quality and conversion efficiency, not just fixating on CTR to make judgments.</p>
<p>Next time you review, ask yourself first: After users click, are they really planning to buy?</p>
